%I A396321 #51 Jul 13 2026 07:06:07
%S A396321 0,0,0,96,12840,239040,2163840,12888960,58042656,213615360,674570160,
%T A396321 1888587360,4797335400,11245730496,24642268560,50981199360,
%U A396321 100370578560,189249592320,343524515616,602905753440,1026789137640,1702093525440,2753544282720,4356978950016,6756347796000,10285188576000
%N A396321 Number of n X n binary matrices with exactly 10 1's such that there are an even number of 1's in every row and column.
%C A396321 Also weight A_10 of the weight distribution for a square n X n Single Parity Check Product (SPCP) code when the 1's represent bit errors, and 0's represent unchanged data bits. For a SPCP code, A_odd = 0, A_4 = C(n,2)^2 = A000537(n-1), A_6 = 3!*C(n,3) = A179058(n), A_8 = A396317(n). See the rectangular formula for other message data formats.
%D A396321 E. R. Berlekamp, Algebraic Coding Theory, McGraw-Hill, New York, 1968, pp. 397-400.
%D A396321 R. E. Blahut, Theory and Practice of Error Control Codes, Addison-Wesley, 1983, p. 431.
%D A396321 C. Leung, Evaluation of the Error Probability of Single Parity-Check Codes, IEEE Transactions on Communications Vol. COM-31, NO. 2, Feb 1983, pp. 250-253.
%D A396321 F. J. MacWilliams, and N. J. A. Sloane The Theory of Error Correcting Codes, Elsevier/North Holland 1977, p. 21.
%D A396321 W. W. Peterson, and E. J. Weldon, Error Correcting Codes, MIT Press, 1994, pp. 64-70, pp. 131-132.
%H A396321 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A396321/b396321.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..100</a>
%H A396321 A. M. Patel, <a href="https://mirrors.meulie.net/bitsavers.org/pdf/ibm/IBM_Journal_of_Research_and_Development/186/ibmrd1806Q.pdf">Optimal Rectangular Code for High Density Magnetic Tapes</a>.
%H A396321 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A396317/a396317_2.pdf">Probability of Undetected Error for Some Simple Product Codes</a>, MS Thesis, UT Arlington TX, May 1984, pp. 35-37.
%F A396321 a(n) = 2040*C(n,5)^2 + 1440*C(n,5)*C(n,4) + 120*C(n,5)*C(n,3) + 96*C(n,4)^2.
%F A396321 a(n) = 1/120*(n - 3)*(n - 2)^2 * (n - 1)^2 * n^2 * (17*n^3 - 127*n^2 + 300*n - 236).
%F A396321 The rectangular formula for the n X k matrices is a(n,k) = 2040*C(n,5)*C(k,5) + 720*C(n,5)*C(k,4) + 720*C(n,4)*C(k,5) + 60*C(n,3)*C(k,5) + 60*C(n,5)*C(k,3) + 96*C(n,4)*C(k,4). This is shown in table form below, where each entry is multiplied by its column header and left row header, then all entries are summed for a(n,k). The square case n X n, is when k = n.
%F A396321   A_10   C(k,2)  C(k,3)  C(k,4)  C(k,5)
%F A396321   C(n,2)    0       0       0       0
%F A396321   C(n,3)    0       0       0      60
%F A396321   C(n,4)    0       0      96     720
%F A396321   C(n,5)    0      60     720    2040
%e A396321 The first formula given above adds the counts of 4 subsets that are categorized by the same number of 1's in rows and columns (with transpositions in the same category).
%e A396321 For n=4, a(4) = 90*0 + 1440*0 + 120*0 + 96 = 96 by the formula. See also the figures below, showing an example for each subset:
%e A396321 .
%e A396321 Subset 1, 5 X 5 exactly 2 1's per row and 2 1's per column.
%e A396321 1 1 0 0 0
%e A396321 0 1 1 0 0   The number of patterns of 2 1's per row and column
%e A396321 0 0 1 1 0   is 2040, see A001499(5).
%e A396321 0 0 0 1 1
%e A396321 1 0 0 0 1
%e A396321 .
%e A396321 Subset 2,  5 X 4, one row with 4 1's. We count the number of patterns in nonzero rows.
%e A396321 1 1 1 1 0  The number of patterns in the first row is 5. The 0 in the first row
%e A396321 0 0 0 1 1  requires a pair of 1's in that column and there are C(3,2) = 3 choices of
%e A396321 0 0 1 0 1  those. The second 0 down from the top in the last right column requires two
%e A396321 1 1 0 0 0  1's in that row, there are C(4,2) = 6 patterns of those. That same row has
%e A396321 0 0 0 0 0  two 0's that have 2 remaining choices in respective columns to add 1's.
%e A396321            The row of 4 can be placed in 4 ways. Finally, a doubling of choices comes
%e A396321            from transposition. Total choices = 5*3*6*2*4*2 = 1440.
%e A396321 .
%e A396321 Subset 3,  5 X 3, two rows with 4 1's. We count the number of patterns in nonzero rows.
%e A396321 1 1 0 0 0  Number of patterns of 2 1's in the first row is C(5,2) = 10.
%e A396321 1 0 1 1 1  The next row of 4 requires a 0 in a shared column of 1 from first row.
%e A396321 0 1 1 1 1  The last row requires a 0 in the shared column of the other 1 from the
%e A396321 0 0 0 0 0  first row. The number of row selections is 3! Finally, a doubling of
%e A396321 0 0 0 0 0  choices comes from transposition. Total choices = 2*3!*C(5,2) = 120.
%e A396321 .
%e A396321 Subset 4,  4 X 4, one row of 4 1's and one column of 4 1's. We count the nonzero row
%e A396321 1 1 1 1 0  and nonzero columns. There are 4 choices for row of 4, and 4 choices for
%e A396321 1 1 0 0 0  column of 4. The remaining part has 6 patterns. Total choices = 4*4*6 = 96.
%e A396321 1 0 1 0 0
%e A396321 1 0 0 1 0
%e A396321 0 0 0 0 0
%e A396321 .
%e A396321 For n=5, a(5) = 2040*1 + 1440*5 + 120*10 + 96*25 = 12840.
%t A396321 A396321[n_] := (n - 3)*(n - 2)^2*(n - 1)^2*n^2*(n*(n*(17*n - 127) + 300) - 236)/120;
%t A396321 Array[A396321, 30] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jul 13 2026 *)
%Y A396321 Cf. A001499, A000537, A179058, A396317.
%K A396321 nonn,easy,new
%O A396321 1,4
%A A396321 _G. Gordon Thompson_, May 21 2026
